[{"id":"VH968102","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH968050.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following explains how the bureaucracy can address a problem shown in the infographic?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH968102_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents an infographic titled “The Cost of Congestion,” which is divided into four sections. In the top left section, a car is shown and the following caption is written below it: “The average American spends 42 hours a year in traffic.” In the top right section, a gas pump is shown and the following caption is written below it: “$160 Billion lost by congestion delays and lost fuel.” In the middle section, a stack of coins is shown and the following caption is written below it: “Middle, and low, income American households spend nearly 20% of income on transportation, and 40% on housing.” In the bottom section, a cargo truck is shown, and the follow caption is written it: “Freight volume is expected to increase by more than 40%.”\" height=\"416\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH968050.g01.png\" width=\"395\" />\n<p class=\"attribution author\">Source: United States Department of Transportation, 2017</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The Department of Transportation can write stronger regulations on freight volume.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The president can negotiate a treaty that would allow for increased imports of oil.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The House Committee on Energy and Commerce can hold a hearing on the cost of fuel.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The Supreme Court can overturn laws that regulate fuel economy.</p>"],"answer":0}]